prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: FOG cores
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Individual pointings to about 50 clump positions, derived from Hi-GAL 250mu image, with clumpfind. All clumps have M > 3 Mo (T=20K)

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: We propose to observe the dust emission at 52 individual positions in a distant (ca. 9.3 kpc) molecular cloud, using single continuum mode (7.5 GHz bandwidth) in Band 6 with the array in its most compact configuration. We want to detect potentially star-forming molecular cores, which are expected to have sizes <0.1 pc and masses of the order of the Jeans mass, ca. 0.6 Mo in this case (T=20K, n=10^5). The dust emission peaks in the far-IR and decreases towards longer wavelengths (lambda^(-2)). Band 6 gives the best combination of sensitivity (at 1mm the dust emission is stronger than in bands 3, 4), resolution (1."6 is 0.07pc, comparable to the expected size of the targets) and max. recoverable scale (11" = 0.44pc; we are expecting cores that are smaller than or comparable to the size of the synthesized beam and are not interested in the more extended inter-core emission component). A mass of 0.6 Mo corresponds to an integrated flux of 0.23 mJy at 1mm. For this to be a 3 sigma detection, the required sensitivity is 0.075 mJy/beam. For 52 pointings we need about 5 hrs, acc. to the time estimator.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: The distribution over mass of stars at birth, the stellar initial mass function (IMF) is one of the most important parameters in star-formation research. What determines the IMF is still not clear, nor is it clear whether the IMF is the same for every star forming region. It does seem, however, that the IMF is set very early on by the masses of the molecular cores out of which the stars form. The core mass function (CMF), and by consequence the IMF, may however depend on the physical and chemical properties of the environment. So far, CMFs (and IMFs) have been determined in molecular clouds (and star clusters) in the solar neighbourhood and the inner Galaxy. We propose to determine the core mass spectrum in a molecular cloud in the far-outer reaches of our Galaxy (galactocentric distance 16 kpc, heliocentric distance 9.3 kpc), where conditions are very different from the inner Galaxy. We will compare our CMF with those of cores in local and inner Galaxy clouds, to see if a different environment has lead to different CMFs. Our target is a cloud with star formation, for which we can also determine the IMF (from other data).
